                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Biceps Short Head</b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Dumbbell bicep curls primarily target the </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519538/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">biceps short head</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">, a muscle located on the front of your upper arm. It forms part of the biceps brachii alongside the long head. The primary function of your biceps short head is to flex and extend your elbow. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During the dumbbell bicep curl, your biceps short head brings the dumbbells up and down as your elbow flexes and extends. Overall, the dumbbell biceps curls are great for developing strength, shape, and definition of the biceps short head.</span></p><p><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/short-head-bicep-exercises" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Short head bicep exercises</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> provide a great way to target this head specifically.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Did you know? During the ascending (lifting) phase, using a </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10054060/#:~:text=The%20supinated%20handgrip%20elicited%20the,found%20during%20the%20descending%20phase." target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">supinated grip</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> resulted in 19% greater activation compared to a pronated grip. It also resulted in 12% greater activation compared to a neutral grip.</span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
