                            <div class="container">
                    <div class="exc-container">
                        <div class="muscle-text bd-bot exercise-list-start">
                            <h3><b>Biceps Long Head </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The long head of the biceps is the larger of the two heads. Alongside the short head, it makes up the majority of your biceps brachii. It also originates from a higher point on the shoulder blade compared to the short head.  </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">During biceps curls, the long head also contracts to turn the palms upwards and bend the elbows as you lift. However, its position plays a more significant role when the shoulder and arms are more stretched. This happens during exercises like incline curls.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is because it has a </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5505302/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">small role</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> in raising your arm straight in front of you. Your long head assists the initial lift and stabilizes the shoulder while the short head handles most of the lifting. These factors are crucial for doing dumbbell biceps curls correctly.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If you’re looking for targetted bicep work, perform </span><a href="https://www.endomondo.com/exercise/best-long-head-bicep-exercises" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">long head bicep exercises</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> to specifically work focus on this head.</span></p><h3><b>Wrist Flexors </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK545198/#:~:text=The%20flexor%20digitorum%20superficialis%20muscle,at%20the%20proximal%20interphalangeal%20joints.&amp;text=The%20flexor%20digitorum%20profundus%20is%20innervated%20medially%20by%20the%20ulnar%20nerve." target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">wrist flexors</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> include different muscles located on the front side of the forearm. These muscles connect your elbows to your hands. They are responsible for bringing your palm closer to the inner part of your arm. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">However, during dumbbell curls, the wrist flexors contract isometrically to stabilize the wrist and maintain a strong grip. This helps prevent the weights from slipping or the wrists rotating excessively during the curling motion. A stable grip can help transfer force to the biceps, improving the efficiency of the exercise. </span></p><h3><b>Wrist Extensors </b></h3><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The wrist extensors include the muscles on the posterior side, or back, of your forearm. Their primary function is to move the back of your hand closer to your forearm.</span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">While they are less actively involved in dumbbell bicep curls, they eccentrically contract to control the lowering phase. This action helps in </span><a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5977047/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener"><span style="font-weight: 400;">maintaining balance and stability</span></a> <span style="font-weight: 400;">throughout the exercise. </span></p><p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Overall, both the wrist flexors and extensors ensure proper execution of dumbbell curls by stabilizing your wrists. </span></p>                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
